04791nam a22006135i 9780520959514DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20142014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209595147 a10.1525/97805209595142doi  a(DE-B1597)520813  a(OCoLC)1102806142  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBR1495.N5bH36 2016 7aREL0940002bisacsh04a279.532231 aHandman, Courtney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCritical Christianity :bTranslation and Denominational Conflict in Papua New Guinea /cCourtney Handman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Anthropology of Christianity ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Sacred Speakers or Sacred Groups: The Colonial Lutheran Church in New Guinea -- t2. Linguistic Locality and the Anti-Institutionalism of Evangelical Christianity: The Summer Institute of Linguistics -- t3. Translating Locality: The Ethno-Linguistics of Christian Critique -- t4. Revival Villages: Experiments in Christian Social and Spatial Groups -- t5. The Surprise of Speech: Disorder, Violence, and Christian Language after the Men's House -- t6. Events of Translation: Intertextuality and Denominationalist Change -- t7. Mediating Denominational Disputes: Land Claims and the Sound of Christian Critique -- t8. Kinship, Christianity, and Culture Critique: Learning to Be a Lost Tribe of Israel in Papua New Guinea -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Critical Christianity, Courtney Handman analyzes the complex and conflicting forms of sociality that Guhu-Samane Christians of rural Papua New Guinea privilege and celebrate as "the body of Christ." Within Guhu-Samane churches, processes of denominational schism-long relegated to the secular study of politics or identity-are moments of critique through which Christians constitute themselves and their social worlds. Far from being a practice of individualism, Protestantism offers local people ways to make social groups sacred units of critique. Bible translation, produced by members of the Summer Institute of Linguistics, is a crucial resource for these critical projects of religious formation. From early interaction with German Lutheran missionaries to engagements with the Summer Institute of Linguistics to the contemporary moment of conflict, Handman presents some of the many models of Christian sociality that are debated among Guhu-Samane Christians. Central to the study are Handman's rich analyses of the media through which this critical Christian sociality is practiced, including language, sound, bodily movement, and everyday objects. This original and thought-provoking book is essential reading for students and scholars of anthropology and religious studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChristian sectszPapua New GuineaxSocial life and customs. 0aGuhu-Samane languagezPapua New Guinea. 0aGuhu-Samane language. 0aLutheran ChurchzPapua New Guinea. 0aProtestantismxSocial aspectszPapua New Guinea. 0aProtestantismzPapua New Guinea. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Denominations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520959514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520959514.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Packag